"Song X., Lubin D., Zhang G.J.","Increased greenhouse gases enhance regional climate response to a Maunder Minimum",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","1", L01703,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL041290,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75749108859&partnerID=40&md5=c0d0936cbb8d4088f9cd17f4ec927a09","Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Dr., La Jolla, CA 92093, United States","Song, X., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Dr., La Jolla, CA 92093, United States; Lubin, D., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Dr., La Jolla, CA 92093, United States; Zhang, G.J., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Dr., La Jolla, CA 92093, United States","The climate responses to the Maunder Minimum-type total solar irradiance (TSI) decrease in the pre-industrial (PI) era and IPCC B1 global warming scenario are examined using the NCAR CAM3 coupled with a mixed-layer slab ocean model. The TSI reduction shifts the AO/NAO state to a more negative index, resulting in regional surface air temperature (SAT) change in the model. In addition, the positive sea ice-solar radiation feedback amplifies the surface cooling due to the TSI decrease. The global annual average cooling effect induced by the TSI decrease is reduced to 0.254°C in the B1 scenario from 0.347°C in the PI epoch, this difference being due to both the suppressed sea ice-olar radiation feedback and the stronger greenhouse effect associated with the increase of greenhouse gases. However, regional SAT changes in the B1 scenario are strengthened markedly due to the enhanced negative AO/NAO. The warming in the western Greenland, Central Asia and East Asia will be enhanced in the B1 global warming scenario when the TSI decreases. These differences in response between the B1 and PI scenarios illustrate that the impact of multi-decadal solar variation on climate depends on the atmospheric background trace gas composition. A future solar grand minimum does not offset the CO 2-induced warming in the B1 scenario, but through the enhanced negative AO/NAO may indeed amplify the warming in certain regions. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Annual average; Central Asia; Cooling effects; East Asia; Greenland; Maunder minimum; Negative index; Pre-industrial; Regional climate; Slab ocean models; Solar variations; Surface air temperatures; Surface cooling; Total solar irradiance; Trace gas; Atmospheric composition; Carbon dioxide; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Greenhouse gases; Greenhouses; Oceanography; Sea ice; Solar radiation; Sun; Climate models; air temperature; climate change; climate effect; global warming; greenhouse gas; Maunder Minimum; North Atlantic Oscillation; paleoclimate; solar radiation; trace gas",,,,,,"Abreu, J.A., Beer, J., Steinhilber, F., Tobias, S.M., Weiss, N.O., For how long will the current grand maximum of solar activity persist? (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L20109. , doi:10.1029/2008GL035442; Collins, W.D., Rasch, P.J., Boville, B.A., Hack, J.J., McCaa, J.R., Williamson, D.L., Briegleb, B.P., Zhang, M., The formulation and atmospheric simulation of the Community Atmosphere Model version 3 (CAM3) (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (11), pp. 2144-2161. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3760.1; Hoyt, D.V., Schatten, K.H., A discussion of plausible solar irradiance variations 1700-1992 (1993) J. Geophys. Res., 98, pp. 18895-18906. , doi:10.1029/93JA01944; Huang, S., Merging information from different resources for new insights into climate change in the past and future (2004) Geophysical Research Letters, 31 (13), pp. 1-4. , DOI 10.1029/2004GL019781; Kiehl, J.T., Shields, C.A., Hack, J.J., Collins, W.D., The climate sensitivity of the Community Climate System Model version 3 (CCSM3) (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (11), pp. 2584-2596. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3747.1; Koslowski, G., Glaser, R., Variations in reconstructed ice winter severity in the Western Baltic from 1501 to 1995, and their implications for the North Atlan